SIMPLE: purvey
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Purvey
<hw>Pur*vey"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Purveyed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Purveying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>purveien</ets>, <ets>porveien</ets>, OF. <ets>porveeir</ets>,
<ets>porveoir</ets>, F. <ets>pourvoir</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>providere</ets>. See <er>Provide</er>, and cf.
<er>Purview</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To furnish or provide, as with
a convenience, provisions, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Give no odds to your foes, but do <qex>purvey</qex>⟦br⟧
Yourself of sword before that bloody day.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To procure; to get.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I mean to <qex>purvey</qex> me a wife after the fashion of the
children of Benjamin.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purvey</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Purvey
<hw>Pur*vey"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To purchase
provisions; to provide; to make provision.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.
Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To pander; -- with <xex>to</xex>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧
Their turpitude <xex>purveys</xex> to their malice.⟦rdquo⟧
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Burke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Purveyance</ent>⟦br⟧
